"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691797","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Valuation Office Agency registers fair rents under the Rent Act 1977 on behalf of my Department. They do not hold information on the number of people who had fair rents registered in Tynemouth constituency or North Tyneside borough.</p><p>The information set out in the table below, relates to the number of registered rents in the Tyne and Wear registration area.</p><p><strong>Fair rent registration in Tyne &amp; Wear (2010 -</strong> <strong>Dec 31</strong> <strong>2015)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of registered rents</strong></p></td><td><p>116</p></td><td><p>149</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>183</p></td><td><p>507</p></td><td><p>547</p></td><td><p>1603</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-28T16:23:56.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691797/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691797/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Rented Housing: Tyne and Wear","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people have had a fair rent registered in (a) Tynemouth constituency and (b) North Tyneside borough since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","64499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691798","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>There are currently no plans to extend the Right to Buy through legislation. However, the Government is clear that where a local authority led local housing company is delivering affordable housing on similar terms to housing in the Housing Revenue Account, those tenants should enjoy comparable rights to tenants of social housing delivered through the Housing Revenue Account.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","64274","2017-03-07T10:25:13.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691798/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691798/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Right to Buy Scheme: Council Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on the number of houses sold of the proposal to extend the right to buy to homes built by council housing companies in the Housing White Paper.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","64500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691799","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-04","<p>The terms and conditions of appointment confirm that the Chair of the Leasehold Advisory Service must declare any personal or business interests which may, or may be perceived to, influence their judgements in performing their functions. These interests are included in a register of interests maintained by LEASE which the Chair is obliged to keep up to date. Should a particular matter give rise to conflict of interest, the Chair is required to inform the Board in advance and withdraw from discussions or consideration of the matter. With these safeguards in place we do not consider it necessary to require the Chair to have no business interests in the leasehold sector.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-04T15:49:00.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691799/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691799/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691799/answer/previousversion/36710","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Leasehold Advisory Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to require whoever is Chair of the Leasehold Advisory Service to have no business interests in the leasehold sector.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691800","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-04","<p>The main purpose of the Leasehold Advisory Service is to support leaseholders by providing impartial free initial advice. It is desirable for Board members of the Leasehold Advisory Service to have knowledge or experience of the housing sector, particularly issues that affect the residential leasehold sector. However, there is no current or planned requirement for at least one member of the Board of the Leasehold Advisory Service to be an independent representative of leaseholders.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-04-04T15:49:30.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691800/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691800/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691800/answer/previousversion/36711","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Leasehold Advisory Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make it his policy to require at least one member of the Board of the Leasehold Advisory Service to be an independent representative of leaseholders.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","64505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691801","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-23","<p>A new home is not just the largest monetary purchase most people ever make, it is also the largest emotional commitment as people look to provide a safe, good quality home for them and their families. It is therefore vital that as housing supply increases, the quality of new build homes continues to improve so as to avoid some of the issues highlighted in the APPG for Excellence in the Built Environment report.</p><p>I am aware of the report’s recommendations, and will consider them, including that for a new homes ombudsman.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-23T16:29:59.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691801/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691801/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Housing: Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing a new homes ombudsman.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","64456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691802","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>Schedule 5 (Paragraph 13) of the Right to Acquire regulations (<a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1997/619/made" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1997/619/made</a>) provides a provision designed to safeguard a landlord who has spent money in respect of a property, including construction, development costs and the acquisition of land. This is similar to the cost floor which applies to the Right to Buy.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-28T16:22:19.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691802/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691802/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the lack of a cost floor on housing associations whose tenants purchase their home through the right to acquire.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","64439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691803","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Supreme Court judgement in the case of Woolway (VO) v Mazars LLP will bring simplicity and consistency to the rating system. The Valuation Office Agency are responsible for implementing the decision independently of Ministers. We will keep this matter under review. From April we are permanently doubling small business rate relief meaning 600,000 small businesses will pay no business rates at all.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-02T18:14:51.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691803/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691803/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Small Businesses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the judgment of 29 July 2015 in Woolway v. Mazars on eligibility for small business rate relief among small businesses.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","64410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691804","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Department does not collect or hold data on local authority selective licensing schemes, which do not require confirmation.</p><p>Since the 1 April 2015, the Secretary of State has confirmed the approval of two schemes (greater than 20 per cent of a local authority's geographical area or private rented stock):</p><p>Burnley Borough Council:</p><ul><li>start date 15 November 2016;</li><li>end date 15 November 2021.</li></ul><p>Peterborough City Council :</p><ul><li>start date 1 November 2016;</li><li>end date 1 November 2021.</li></ul>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-07T10:25:56.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691804/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691804/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691804/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Private Rented Housing: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have in place a selective licence scheme for private rented properties within their area; when each such scheme began; and when each such scheme is due to end or need renewal.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","64411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691805","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>Ministers and officials in my department meet regularly with the Department of Health to discuss a wide range of issues. The 2015 Spending Review reaffirmed the Government's commitment to implementing these reforms in April 2020, making funding available in 2019/20 to help local authorities prepare for implementation. Ahead of that, the Department of Health will continue to review the detail, to ensure that the new system can work from day 1, and my officials will engage with them on this.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-28T16:13:42.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691805/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691805/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691805/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with Ministerial colleagues at the Department of Health on (a) how the proposed cap on residential care costs is to be funded and (b) when that cap is planned to be implemented.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","64340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691806","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-20","<p>We are unable to provide details of contracts that may have been awarded with a value of less than £10,000 as locating, retrieving and extracting this expenditure would have been at a disproportionate cost.</p><p>The table below sets out the answer to (a) and (b): the number of contracts and their total values that had been let by my Department since 2010-11.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>No of contracts</p></td><td><p>Total Value of contracts</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010 - 11</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>£20 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011 - 12</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>£50 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012 - 13</p></td><td><p>84</p></td><td><p>£89 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 14</p></td><td><p>109</p></td><td><p>£39 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 - 15</p></td><td><p>148</p></td><td><p>£41 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 - 16</p></td><td><p>91</p></td><td><p>£40 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>My Department does not hold information on the value of pro bono costs and the number of work days contracted out.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-20T15:34:38.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691806/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691806/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691806/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Department for Communities and Local Government: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by his Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate he has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691807","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-16","<p>Records show the Department has spent £138.22 on Uber taxi fares in the last six months.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-03-16T14:24:43.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691807/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691807/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691807/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Department for Communities and Local Government: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much his Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691808","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Home Office does not collect information on pump stations. Official statistics on the total number of fire stations in England are available in Table 1403 here</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#other" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables#other</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-23T12:37:25.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691808/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691808/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691808/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Fire Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish a list of all three pump fire stations in England, by name and local authority.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","64686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691809","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>My Department launched the Own Your Home campaign in October 2015 – aimed at persuading young working people to look again at home ownership and driving take up of appropriate government home-buying schemes when this is the right decision for them. This overarching campaign also draws together communications activity on a range of government schemes. Prior to this, campaigns on Right to Buy and Help to Buy had been run separately since 2012.</p><p>Own Your Home specific activity is delivered at a national level and cannot be disaggregated down to regional or local authority level. Spend on this campaign was £2.08 million in 2015/16 and £3.517 million in 2016/17</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-01T17:12:51.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691809/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691809/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691809/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Home Ownership Incentive Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much has been spent from the public purse on advertising and other promotional material for the Own Your Home initiatives in each year since 2010-11 by (a) region, (b) local authority area and (c) constituency.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","64665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691810","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Government gave nearly £14 million from 2010 to 2016 to develop a programme to help single homeless people access private rented sector accommodation, as part of its work to prevent and tackle homelessness. Our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme is now funding 84 projects in 225 local authorities, following an open competition last autumn, details of which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584760/Homelessness_Prevention_Programme_-_Successful_bids.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584760/Homelessness_Prevention_Programme_-_Successful_bids.pdf</a></p><p>Some of these projects will help single homeless people access and sustain housing in the private rental sector. For example, Bristol City Council are setting up a team to do early intervention work with households in the private rented sector who are at risk of homelessness to prevent a crisis.</p><p>We are also going further and supporting the honourable member for Harrow East’s Homelessness Reduction Bill, which will significantly reform the support people receive to prevent homelessness. The Government has committed to provide £61 million to local authorities to meet the costs of the Bill.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-03-01T14:08:31.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691810/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691810/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the criteria are for the Government's decisions on how much funding for help to rent projects to allocate to local authorities; and whether the Government plans to increase such funding.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","64621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691811","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Government is committed to preventing homelessness. Access to the private rented sector plays a part in both preventing and supporting the recovery from homelessness, helping people rebuild their lives.</p><p>We made a significant investment of nearly £14 million from 2010 to 2016 for Crisis to develop a programme to help single homeless people access private rented sector accommodation. Over 9,000 people were helped, with over 90 per cent maintaining tenancies for at least 6 months.</p><p>In addition, our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme is funding 84 projects in 225 local authorities. It provides an end-to-end approach to preventing and tackling homelessness and rough sleeping, and will support a wide range of initiatives in local areas to prevent homelessness and enable people to recover quickly from a crisis.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-28T17:33:20.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691811/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691811/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691811/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-02-20","Private Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much funding for help to rent projects the Government has provided to local authorities in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","64623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691812","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>The UK’s negotiations for exiting the EU will be complex and the Government is focused on securing the best deal for Britain. We continue to engage with businesses and key stakeholders in the horseracing and bloodstock industries. We will listen to their concerns and ensure our new relationship with the EU works for business and consumers.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-23T17:11:49.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691812/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691812/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Horse Racing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with relevant stakeholders on the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on horse-racing and bloodstock industries in the UK and Ireland.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","64597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691813","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>Since 2010, Sport England has invested £39,097 in cricket projects in St Helens, £305,466 in Merseyside and £3,035,554 in the North West. In addition, Sport England have recently agreed funding of £7.6m for the ECB to deliver cricket nationally between 2017 and 2021.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-23T12:56:00.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691813/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691813/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Cricket: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to promote and develop cricket in (a) St Helens, (b) Merseyside and (c) the North West.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","64598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691814","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>Horseracing is enjoyed by many and makes a significant contribution to Britain’s economy. A 2013 report from Deloitte for the British Horseracing Authority estimated that British racing has a Great Britain-wide economic impact of £3.45 billion. We do not hold specific figures on the contribution of the horse racing industry to the economy in the North West.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-23T17:02:27.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691814/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691814/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Horse Racing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate her Department has made of the contribution of the horse-racing industry to the economy in the (a) North West and (b) UK.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","64595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691815","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>Funding provided to public libraries in England in each of the last 5 years by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport and through Arts Council England, the development agency for libraries, is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong> <strong>budgeted</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>DCMS </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>£2,589,626</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£4,300,000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Arts Council England</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£983,405 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£3,960,601 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£2,675,015 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£3,077,350<br> <br> <br> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£2,500,000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£983,405 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£3,960,601</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£2,675,015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£5,666,976</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£6,800,000</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p>This is in addition to the net investment by local library authorities annually including £701 million in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>The funding from DCMS in 2015/16 supported the installation or significant upgrade of WiFi in public libraries across England, while the funding for 2016/17 includes a new public libraries innovation fund to support projects that develop innovative library service activity to benefit disadvantaged people and places in England.</p><p> </p><p>Arts Council England's funding provided to public libraries in England supports library-specific activity or direct investment in a library, such as the Get It Loud In Libraries programme which has created exciting opportunities for young people to lead, participate, volunteer and excel in artistic and cultural activity in a library environment.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-02-28T15:51:36.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691815/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691815/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what funding she has provided to libraries in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","64667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691816","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-22","<p>My department has made no direct payments to Uber for business travel or otherwise.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-22T12:01:47.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691816/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691816/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much her Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691817","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-03-08","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-03-08T11:11:17.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691817/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691817/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by her Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate she has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691818","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-23T15:27:41.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691818/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691818/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Broadband: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much information her Department holds on the number of metres of last-mile copper line laid or refurbished over the last five years which was funded from the public purse.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","64348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691819","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>Local authorities have a statutory duty to provide a comprehensive and efficient library service and are responsible for funding the public library service. Some local authorities do also provide short term funding to assist community groups with running costs or one off grants to take over the running of the library.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is providing support for library services and other public sector organisations to consider alternative funding and delivery models, including public service mutuals which can involve local communities as well as library staff having a stake in the public services.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-02-23T16:58:59.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691819/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691819/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Public Libraries: Voluntary Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what government funding is available to community groups who wish to take over the running of libraries from local authorities.","false","Biography information for Mr David Nuttall","Bury North","Mr David Nuttall","64455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691820","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>The UK has a competitive mobile communications market and the independent regulator Ofcom is responsible for promoting competition to further the interests of consumers, both before and after the forthcoming spectrum auction.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-23T12:48:46.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691820/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691820/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Mobile Phones: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what her plans are to ensure that there is sufficient competition in the mobile phone industry after the sale of mobile phone spectrum.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","64457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691821","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>None.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-23T15:28:09.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691821/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691821/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Broadband: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the number of metres of copper line laid by British Telecom in 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","64364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691822","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2017-02-28","<p><del class="ministerial">Through the Government’s National Cyber Security Programme, my Department is delivering an ambitious set of initiatives to support the growth of and investment in cyber security companies across the United Kingdom, including those from Northern Ireland. In particular, we provide opportunities for early stage companies from across the UK to be represented at selected events where they can showcase their technologies and expertise in order to secure investment. We are also funding the delivery of two cyber innovation centres which are open to companies from across the UK.</del></p><p><del class="ministerial">We are also funding the delivery of ‘Hut Zero’, an accelerator programme for individuals with cyber security ideas , and ‘Cyber 101’ business training ‘bootcamps’ for early stage companies, some of which are being delivered in Northern Ireland. I am particularly delighted that Queen’s University Belfast’s Centre for Secure Information Technology is playing a pivotal role in the delivery of both of those initiatives.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">DCMS is committed to offering all applicants equality of opportunity to ensure that we attract and retain candidates with the most talent and potential. To this end, the DCMS recruitment process does not require applicants to declare unspent criminal convictions at the initial recruitment stage. Applicants are asked to declare unspent criminal convictions as part of basic employment checks when a provisional offer of employment has been made. Decisions concerning appointment to a post where an individual has a conviction history are made on a case-by-case basis.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"><strong> </strong></ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The department does not retain details centrally that would allow us to identify employees with unspent convictions so the information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</ins></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-28T17:40:34.42Z","2017-03-01T11:18:54.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691822/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691822/answer","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691822/answer/previousversion/37703","Biography information for Matt Hancock","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many equality impact assessments have been carried out in the last three years on public service reforms which impact on (a) departmental staff and (b) members of the public; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","64441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691823","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>DCMS is committed to offering all applicants equality of opportunity to ensure that we attract and retain candidates with the most talent and potential. To this end, the DCMS recruitment process does not require applicants to declare unspent criminal convictions at the initial recruitment stage. Applicants are asked to declare unspent criminal convictions as part of basic employment checks when a provisional offer of employment has been made. Decisions concerning appointment to a post where an individual has a conviction history are made on a case-by-case basis.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not retain details centrally that would allow us to identify employees with unspent convictions so the information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-28T17:38:51.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691823/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691823/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691824","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>We, and other Departments, are working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-28T17:42:02.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691824/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691824/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691825","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-23","<p>The importance of partnerships was one of the key themes of the Government's Culture White Paper which was published in March 2016 and we were clear that better collaboration between cultural sectors and partners at a local, regional and national level will help support communities and their access to culture.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-23T12:51:18.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691825/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691825/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to promote the sharing of facilities between different areas of the arts.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691826","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-28","<p>Through the Football Foundation, the Government is investing £18 million each year in partnership with the Premier League and The FA to amateur football clubs, schools, councils and local sports associations to support the development of new or refurbished local football facilities. This includes facilities that greatly improve the access to disabled people as users of these sites.</p><p> </p><p>Over and above merely increasing access and opportunities for disabled sports people to play regular sport, many of these facilities also become key venues at which disability-focused community programmes are delivered by professional football clubs’ trusts, charities and other organisations.</p><p> </p><p>These schemes often achieve multiple social outcomes beyond sport, such as improving the health and wellbeing of disabled players. These schemes also engage many different types of disability, including wheelchair football, visually-impaired and blind football, and deaf and hearing-impaired football.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Act 2010 requires that ‘reasonable adjustments’ are made by service providers, which include the owners of football stadia, to make premises accessible for disabled people. It is for individual clubs to determine what adjustments are ‘reasonable’ taking into account their own circumstances. Structural changes are not always necessary to make sports grounds accessible to spectators with disabilities. Clubs can also change policies and procedures to make their grounds more accessible to disabled spectators.</p><p> </p><p>The Football Stadia Improvement Fund, which is funded by the Premier League, provides money for clubs in the Football League and The FA National League System down to step 7 who want to improve their facilities for players, officials and spectators. Bids to the Fund must enable clubs to meet the membership conditions of their particular leagues, but clubs may also be eligible to apply for funding to provide facilities for disabled spectators. Further information can be found at:www.fsif.co.uk/.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-28T17:52:29.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691826/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691826/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-02-20","Football: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what financial support she provides to small football clubs to improve disabled access at such clubs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691827","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The draft Digital Government (Disclosure of Information) Regulations, available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535311/2016-07-05_Digital_Government__Disclosure_of_Information__draft_regs.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535311/2016-07-05_Digital_Government__Disclosure_of_Information__draft_regs.pdf</a>, give illustrative examples of the public service delivery purposes for which information may be disclosed.</p><p>The draft Regulations include:</p><p>i) supporting individuals or households who face multiple disadvantages;</p><p>ii) assisting people living in fuel poverty; and</p><p>iii) providing assistance to people who lose access to television broadcasts as a result of upcoming changes to the use of the electromagnetic spectrum.</p><p>Under the provisions of the Digital Economy Bill, information may also be disclosed for the purposes of assisting people living in water poverty. The Digital Economy Bill allows for further regulations to be made that change, including adding further purposes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-23T13:52:51.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691827/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691827/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-20","Digital Economy Bill 2016-17","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the letter of 14 February 2017 from the Minister of State for Digital and Culture to the hon Member for Birkenhead, which services and benefits he plans to include within the affirmative procedures for public service delivery under the Digital Economy Bill.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","64586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691828","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union to ensure there is a detailed understanding of how withdrawal from the European Union will affect Defence.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-27T16:35:29.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691828/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691828/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691829","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is committed to improving diversity of opportunity and creating an inclusive working environment that attracts the best talent, and makes the most of potential skills and productivity.</p><p>The MOD is working with the Cabinet Office to implement the principles of the Ban the Box campaign.</p><p>The information requested relating to how many Ministry of Defence Service and civilian employees have unspent convictions could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-23T16:13:28.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691829/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691829/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Ministry of Defence: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of his Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691830","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-28","<p>Over the last three years the Ministry of Defence (MOD) has had, and continues to have due regard, as necessary, to the public sector equality duty in exercising its functions. The Equality Act does not require this due regard to take the form of an equality impact assessment, nor does it define an equality impact assessment, and the MOD does not maintain a record of such assessments.&quot;</p><p>The MOD aims to ensure that all public service reforms impacting on its staff or members of the public undergo an Equality Analysis, in line with the Public Sector Equality Duty placed on the Department by Equalities legislation. We have recently reviewed and updated our Equality Analysis guidance to ensure that those working on policy, projects, or services have a clear and efficient process to follow and all the necessary tools at hand to undertake an Equality Analysis.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-28T16:01:00.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691830/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691830/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Ministry of Defence: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many equality impact assessments have been carried out in the last three years on public service reforms which impact on (a) departmental staff and (b) members of the public; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","64442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691831","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The UK's attack submarines are meeting their operational tasking and will continue to do so over the coming years as the current Trafalgar Class are replaced with the new Astute Class . I am withholding information on their respective planned out-of-service and in-service dates as disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","64490","2017-02-24T13:35:44.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691831/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691831/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Trafalgar Class Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the scheduled end-of-service date is for each Trafalgar class submarine.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691832","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The UK's attack submarines are meeting their operational tasking and will continue to do so over the coming years as the current Trafalgar Class are replaced with the new Astute Class . I am withholding information on their respective planned out-of-service and in-service dates as disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","64489","2017-02-24T13:35:44.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691832/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691832/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Astute Class Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the timescales for the in-service delivery of Astute class boats are.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691833","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>The UK has a long term commitment to Afghanistan, with 500 troops deployed as part of NATO's Resolute Support Mission. Our core outputs are improving the capability of the Afghan security institutions, developing the Afghan National Army Officer Academy, mentoring the Afghan Air Force and providing vital support for NATO in Kabul through command of the Kabul Security Force.</p><p>We maintain regular dialogue with NATO on the future of the mission in Afghanistan, including through the UK Delegation to NATO, our team working in Resolute Support Headquarters in Kabul, and at meetings of NATO Chief of Defence Staffs, the last of which was held in January. My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State also had the opportunity to discuss Afghanistan with fellow NATO Defence Ministers at the NATO Defence Ministerial Meeting, held on 15-16 February.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-23T16:15:22.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691833/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691833/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Afghanistan: Peacekeeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent discussions his Department has had with NATO on the UK contribution to Operation Resolute Support and the number of UK personnel supporting that operation.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691834","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>The UK currently has around 70 Armed Forces personnel deployed in South Sudan. This number will rise to almost 400 in the coming months as an engineering taskforce and medics are deployed to support the United Nations Mission in the country.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-27T16:39:01.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691834/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691834/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","South Sudan: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK armed forces personnel are deployed in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691835","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The UK is a major partner in the F-35 Lightning II programme, resulting in significant contracts and supporting UK jobs. UK industry will provide approximately 15% by value of every F-35 Lightning to be built.</p><p>Additionally, the UK was recently chosen to be a global hub for maintenance, repair, overhaul and upgrade services for F-35 avionic and aircraft components. Although, these activities will contribute to UK gross domestic product (GDP), the Ministry of Defence does not routinely calculate the GDP impact of specific defence activities and therefore no assessment has been undertaken for the F-35 programme.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-24T13:36:55.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691835/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691835/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the value to UK national gross domestic product of the Global F-35 Lightning II programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691836","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-27","<p>Within the UK, responsibility for Service children with an autism diagnosis rests with the statutory authorities. Where appropriate, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) Directorate for Children and Young People provides additional support. This includes detailed information, advice and support to Service parents through the MOD's Children's Education Advisory Service; and the MOD's Education Support Fund has provided additional resources in situations where a Service child with an autism diagnosis might otherwise suffer disadvantage through Service mobility or parental deployment. For those eligible for the MOD's Continuity of Education Allowance, an addition to that allowance is available to those with an autism diagnosis.</p><p>For Service families based overseas the MOD acts in lieu of a local authority to provide support. Service families are not assigned to an overseas location without an assessment of whether any significant health, welfare or education needs (including autism) can be properly supported. MOD schools overseas have access to trained individuals (including educational psychologists) and training resources to allow schools to support children with autism; and to provide training to parents where practicable. Additional support is also provided for children returning to the United Kingdom, to assure a smooth transition back to local authority responsibility.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-27T16:30:46.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691836/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691836/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Autism: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what support his Department provides for servicemen and women's children who have an autism diagnosis.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","64426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691837","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>A key commitment from the Wales Summit in 2014 is NATO Adaptation, which builds on the work of Allied Command (Transformation).</p><p>Government Ministers regularly discuss the need to reform NATO with their counterparts, and did so again at the NATO Defence Ministerial Meeting on 15/16 February 2017.</p><p>The UK continues to push NATO to become a genuinely adaptable Alliance that is less bureaucratic, faster and better at making decisions, and is able to respond more effectively to a wide range of threats, including cyber, hybrid, and international terrorism.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-23T16:08:37.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691837/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691837/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the Government's policy is on NATO Transformation.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","64514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691838","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>As at 22 February 2017, there are 61 UK Officers attached to NATO’s Supreme Allied Command (Transformation). The information requested can be found in the attached table.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-23T16:10:30.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691838/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691838/answer","64515 - Armed Forces Officers by rank and position attached to NATO Transformation Command.docx","UK Officers attached to NATO's Transformation Cmd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691838/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many officers in the armed forces, at what rank and position, are attached to NATO Transformation Command.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","64515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691839","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-23T16:13:54.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691839/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691839/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Ministry of Defence: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by his Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate he has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691840","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>It is not possible to provide the amount the Ministry of Defence has spent on Uber taxis as individuals are not required to record the companies used when booking travel.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-23T16:11:57.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691840/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691840/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Ministry of Defence: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691841","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Ministry of Defence defines physical security breaches as incidents relating to the loss, theft, or compromise, or the potential loss, theft, or compromise of classified physical assets; for example weapons, explosives, ammunition, and other items which are attractive to criminal or terrorist organisations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-23T16:15:49.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691841/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691841/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Military Bases: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2017 to Question 59060, what sort of activities his Department defines as physical security breaches.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","64613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691842","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The overall manning situation has improved. However, the lack of manpower - particularly in the Defence Equipment and Support area - remains an extant risk and is kept under review. Since the Department's Major Projects Portfolio data for 2015 was published, the number of specialist personnel to support the programme from both the Royal Air Force and Royal Navy has been increased and these additional people have now started to be posted into roles supporting the Lightning Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","64607","2017-02-24T13:38:01.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691842/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691842/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Department's Major Projects Portfolio data 2015, published in July 2016, whether the increasing risk to Initial Capability of the F-35 Lightning II programme as a result of manning issues is extant.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691843","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-24","<p>The overall manning situation has improved. However, the lack of manpower - particularly in the Defence Equipment and Support area - remains an extant risk and is kept under review. Since the Department's Major Projects Portfolio data for 2015 was published, the number of specialist personnel to support the programme from both the Royal Air Force and Royal Navy has been increased and these additional people have now started to be posted into roles supporting the Lightning Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","64606","2017-02-24T13:38:01.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691843/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691843/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-02-20","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Department's Major Projects Portfolio data 2015, published in July 2016, whether the number of Royal Navy and Royal Air Force specialists required to support the F-35 Lightning II programme capability has been increased.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691844","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>As schools embed the new National Curriculum we are monitoring the effect of implementation on teacher workload, pupils with special educational needs and disability and school budgets in a number of ways.</p><p> </p><p>We introduced the Department for Education (DfE) Protocol in 2015 giving schools a minimum lead in time for significant changes to policy in accountability, curriculum and qualifications; to help us manage the impact of reforms on schools.</p><p>We will shortly publish the results of the first biennial survey into teacher workload, a commitment from the 2014 Workload Challenge, which will help us track teacher workload so that so that further action can be taken if needed.</p><p>Through our careful management of the economy, we have protected the core schools budget in real terms. That means that in 2017-18, schools will have more funding than ever before for children’s education, totalling over £40 billion.</p><p>We will continue to support schools to improve their financial health and efficiency, to maximise the amount of resources they can direct to improving outcomes for pupils.</p><p> </p><p>The Department regularly collects and publishes data about schools in the Teacher Voice surveys; the most recently published report includes information about the progress of pupils with special educational needs: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584503/Teacher_Voice_Summer_2016_Report_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/584503/Teacher_Voice_Summer_2016_Report_Final.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The National Curriculum framework inclusion statement sets out that lessons should be planned to ensure that there are no barriers to every pupil achieving. In many cases, such planning will mean that pupils with special educational needs and disability will be able to study the full National Curriculum. Where the full National Curriculum is not the most appropriate route to maximising pupils' education, disapplication of all or part of the National Curriculum may be considered for an individual or a group of pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:08:36.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691844/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691844/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has to evaluate the effect of the implementation of the new national curriculum on (a) teacher workload, (b) Special and Educational Needs and Disability inclusion and (c) school budgets.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","64588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691845","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>My Rt. Hon Friend the Secretary of State regularly visits a wide range of schools across the country. She does not currently have plans to visit a school in Haringey in the next six months.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-23T13:08:10.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691845/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Schools: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 February 2017 to Question 63434, whether she plans to visit any schools in Haringey in the next six months.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691846","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>No formal requests for use of the power can been made while the Children and Social Work Bill is still being considered by parliament, but we have set out some initial examples of ideas by some of our Partner in Practice local authorities. However, there is no automatic presumption they would be granted. Before any exemption would be allowed, applications would need to go through a rigorous scrutiny process as set out in the Bill.</p><p>All of the examples can be found in the published policy statement or Hansard:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/search/Debates?searchTerm=children%20and%20social%20work%20bill&amp;house=Commons" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/search/Debates?searchTerm=children%20and%20social%20work%20bill&amp;house=Commons</a></p><p><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/files/DEP2016-0760/Power_to_innovate_-_policy_statement.pdf" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/files/DEP2016-0760/Power_to_innovate_-_policy_statement.pdf</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-23T12:57:35.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691846/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691846/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Minister of State for Vulnerable Children and Families' reference to local authorities seeking exemptions during the committee stage of the Children and Social Work Bill on 10 January 2017, if she will publish a list of those local authorities and which exemptions they sought.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","64674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691847","Department for Education","false","2017-02-27","<p>Primary and secondary schools can choose to teach the Welsh language to pupils if there is sufficient demand. It is possible for a pupil in England to take privately a Welsh language GCSE offered in Wales if an examination centre is willing to enter them. This will include a revised Welsh Second Language GCSE which will be available for first teaching from September 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-27T14:33:45.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691847/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691847/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Welsh Language: Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department has any plans to introduce the teaching of Welsh as an optional modern language in schools on the England-Wales border.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","64655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691848","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>We do not hold records of any meetings about children’s social care between Ministers at the Department for Education and G4S, Serco or Virgin Care in the last two years.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-23T13:11:20.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691848/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691848/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what meetings her Ministers have had with (a) G4S, (b) Serco and (c) Virgin Care on children's social care in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","64675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691849","Department for Education","false","2017-03-01","<p>The Church of England and the Archbishop of Canterbury have responded positively to our proposal to expand the number of high-quality faith schools. The Church of England has worked with us to deliver new places through the free schools programme and they have opened 14 free schools to date.</p><p>As the Archbishop made clear in his article in the Times Education Supplement of 23 September 2016, the Church of England are drawing up ambitious plans to open many more free schools. We look forward to receiving those applications.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-01T15:51:48.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691849/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691849/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Free Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the article in The Times of 14 February 2017 in the name of the Minister of State for School Standards, what evidence her Department has for the positive response of the Archbishop of Canterbury to proposals to lift the 50 per cent cap on religious selection by free schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","64669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691850","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>The letter sent from the Chief Social Worker to local authorities, regarding the Children and Social Work Bill has been placed in the House library, where it is accessible to members of both Houses.</p><p>The intent of this letter was to provide local authorities with additional information on the Bill and received no direct responses.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-23T17:24:38.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691850/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691850/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish the (a) letter sent from the chief social worker to local authorities in October 2016 on the Children and Social Work Bill and (b) responses received.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","64676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691851","Department for Education","false","2017-03-02","<p>A copy of the data requested has been placed in the Library. The data tells us that 68% of two year olds are taking up their entitlement to funded early learning, an increase of 10% from January 2015.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-02T15:05:13.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691851/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691851/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Pre-school Education: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number and proportion of eligible two-year-olds who have not taken up a funded early education place (a) nationally and (b) in each local authority.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","64677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691852","Department for Education","false","2017-03-02","<p>A copy of the data requested has been placed in the Library.</p><p>The results from the 2016 Early Years Foundation Stage Profile (EYFSP) show that 54% of children with free school meal eligibility achieved a good level of development in their reception year, compared to 72% of all other children. This gap has continued to narrow year on year – from 19.0 percentage points in 2013 to 17.3 percentage points in 2016.</p><p>We know, however, there is more to do, and that is why social mobility is at the heart of the Government’s agenda, and why we are investing a record amount in childcare - £6 billion per year by the end of this Parliament.</p><p>We are working hard to ensure parents and children - wherever they live in England - have access to high quality early years education places through the funded 15 hour entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds and for all three- and four-year-olds.</p><p> </p><p>The Early Years Pupil Premium provides over £300 per eligible child to improve outcomes for disadvantaged children. The Department is also investing £72m to address social mobility challenges in 12 Opportunity Areas across the country. Opportunity Areas will take a life course approach that runs from the early years through to university access and technical education</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-02T15:06:11.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691852/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691852/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the extent of any early years development gap measured by the Early Years Foundation Stage between those children eligible for free school meals and their peers (a) nationally and (b) in each local authority for the last 12 months for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","64678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691853","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>In 2016-17, the national average funding rate that local authorities receive from central government for delivering the two-year-old entitlement is £5.09 per hour per child. From April 2017, the national average funding rate will increase to £5.39 per hour.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-23T13:28:13.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691853/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691853/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate she has made of how much has been allocated from the public purse on average to local authorities for each early years place for a two-year-old eligible for a free early education place.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","64680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691854","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Department does not hold the data requested. The number and proportion of two-year-olds benefitting from funded early education are available in tables 1LA and 5LA in the main tables at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/education-provision-children-under-5-years-of-age-january-2016</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-23T13:23:08.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691854/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691854/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what number and proportion of eligible two-year-olds who benefit from  early years education are among the lowest quintile of disadvantaged two-year-olds.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","64681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691855","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>We want all pupils to be healthy and active. That is why PE remains a compulsory subject at all four key stages in the national curriculum, and why since 2013 the government has provided over £600m of ring-fenced funding through the Primary PE and Sport Premium to help improve the quality of PE provision.</p><p> </p><p>This funding is making a big impact. In independent research, schools reported almost universally that the PE and Sport Premium had had a positive impact on pupils’ physical fitness, with 84 per cent of schools reporting an increase in pupil engagement in PE and in the levels of participation in extra-curricular activities.</p><p> </p><p>We know however, that there is more to do to, which is why we are using revenue from the soft drinks industry levy to double the primary PE and Sport Premium to £320 million a year from September 2017. This is part of wider government work, including the recent Sports Strategy and Childhood Obesity Plan, to help cut obesity levels and increase rates of physical activity.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-23T17:25:38.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691855/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691855/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Exercise: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent steps her Department has taken to promote physical activity among school pupils.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","64690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691856","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Department for Education made no payments to Uber for Business from 28th October 2016 to 20th February 2017.</p><p> </p><p>We do not have access to this information. The Department for Education reimburses employees’ expenses via an online expenses system. All personal reimbursement for taxi fares are classified as ‘Taxis’, and the name of the company is not recorded.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:57:30.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691856/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691856/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691856/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Department for Education: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691857","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:51:33.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691857/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691857/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691857/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Department for Education: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by her Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate she has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691858","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Department for Education welcomes hearing parents’ views on staff qualifications for those working in the early years.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly undertake a comprehensive survey of parents’ use of childcare and early years provision, and their views and experiences. As part of this survey parents are asked what factors they deem important in determining high quality provision, including the qualification levels of staff.</p><p> </p><p>The childcare and early years survey of parents 2014-15 can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/516924/SFR09-2016_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Parents_Survey_2014-15_report.pdf.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/516924/SFR09-2016_Childcare_and_Early_Years_Parents_Survey_2014-15_report.pdf.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Department recently conducted a consultation on the appropriate qualification requirements for early years staff operating at Level 3. This consultation was open to responses from anybody with an interest in the early years sector, including parents.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:56:25.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691858/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691858/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691858/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Nurseries: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what consultation her Department has conducted with parents on nursery staff qualifications.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","64496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691859","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Department does not use a workforce supply model for early years initial teacher training. We have an ambition to grow the number of graduates who are entering the early years teaching profession, and make places available to meet the demand from the market.</p><p> </p><p>Funding is available for training course fees, with additional funding for nursery employers to help them support graduates in their setting to become early years teachers. To encourage the best graduates into the early years workforce we provide bursaries to eligible trainees.</p><p>The workforce strategy will help employers attract, retain and develop staff to deliver high quality provision across the early years sector. As part of the strategy we are considering what government can do to help grow the graduate workforce in the sector.</p><p>The workforce strategy will be published shortly.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:52:49.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691859/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691859/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691859/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Pre-school Education: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many early years teachers she expects to be recruited over the course of this Parliament; and whether the new early years workforce strategy will include details of dedicated funding for the recruitment of new early years teachers.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","64494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691860","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>We want all children, regardless of their background, to have the best possible start in life and to have access to high quality early education and childcare to prepare them for school.</p><p>The results from the 2016 Early Years Foundation Stage Profile show that 54% of children with free school meal eligibility achieved a good level of development in their reception year, compared to 72% of all other children. This gap has continued to narrow year on year - from 19.0 percentage points in 2013 to 17.3 percentage points in 2016.</p><p>However we know there is more to do, and that is why social mobility is at the heart of the Government’s agenda, and why we are investing a record amount in childcare - £6 billion per year by the end of this Parliament.</p><p>During the last Parliament we extended our offer of 15 hours a week of free early education to the 40% most disadvantaged 2-year olds, and introduced the Early Years Pupil Premium - worth £300 per year per eligible child - to help providers close the gap between disadvantaged 3- and 4-year olds and their peers.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:54:45.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691860/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691860/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691860/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that the poorest children start primary school with a good level of development.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","64495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691861","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>Over the last three years the Department for Education has had and continues to have due regard, as necessary, to the public sector equality duty in exercising its functions. The Equality Act does not require this due regard to take the form of an equality impact assessment, nor does it define an equality impact assessment, and the Department does not maintain a record of such assessments.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:59:08.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691861/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691861/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691861/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Department for Education: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many equality impact assessments have been carried out in the last three years on public service reforms which impact on (a) departmental staff and (b) members of the public; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","64443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691862","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Department for Education’s recruitment policies are fully compliant with the Ban the Box initiative. The Department does not hold information about how many employees have unspent convictions.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-28T17:58:05.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691862/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691862/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691862/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Department for Education: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691863","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Department for Education is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-23T16:26:09.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691863/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691863/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691863/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691864","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>We, and other Departments, are working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union. This is to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawal will affect domestic policies and to coordinate policy work across Government.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-28T09:27:35.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691864/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691864/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691864/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691865","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>GM foods and the crops they are derived from are subject to a robust safety assessment and will only be approved for release or marketing if they do not pose a serious risk to human health and the environment. The centralised EU assessment process is overseen by the European Food Safety Authority, with UK Ministers also receiving independent scientific advice on the environmental safety of GM crops from the Advisory Committee on Releases to the Environment.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T12:08:39.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691865/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691865/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691865/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Genetically Modified Organisms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that GM food products are safe to eat and do not harm the environment.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691866","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Government does not offer any direct support to plant mature trees. The Government recognises that planting larger older trees can be a key element in landscaping urban development and an important component of green infrastructure. However, the transportation of mature trees and the soil associated with their roots is a significant pathway in the transportation and establishment of tree pests and diseases, such as Oak Processionary Moth. Therefore the Government strongly recommends that those planting mature trees should source trees that have been grown in the UK or supplied from nurseries with adequate biosecurity procedures in place.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T11:43:13.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691866/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691866/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Tree Planting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to encourage the planting of mature trees.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691867","Department of Health","false","2017-02-23","<p>Legislation requires that all packaging in contact with food must not transfer harmful chemicals into that food. The onus is on food businesses to ensure that the fast food packaging they use is compliant with the legislation. Local enforcement authorities carry out checks to ensure compliance and any products that do not comply are withdrawn from sale.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-23T15:04:19.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691867/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691867/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-20","Fast Food: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that fast food wrappers do not contain substances which are harmful to human health.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691868","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Veterinary Medicines Directorate is working closely with the veterinary profession and livestock sectors to embed responsible use of antibiotics both in stewardship plans and within farm assurance scheme standards and also to set sector-specific targets for reducing antibiotic use by the end of 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Following recommendations made by the Independent Review on AMR, Defra committed to a reduction of 20% in overall antibiotic use in farming by 2018. The most recent data from 2015 show that overall sales of antibiotics for use in livestock dropped by 10%. The government is also considering how future agricultural policy might incentivise high animal health and welfare systems of production.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T12:32:29.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691868/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691868/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Agriculture: Antibiotics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to discourage farming methods which lead to the overuse of antibiotics.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","64565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691869","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>Leaving the EU provides us with an opportunity to redesign our agricultural policy so that it works for the UK, making farming more profitable, competitive and environmentally sustainable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra officials are currently undertaking analysis on future implications for farming. To support this, we will be holding a series of events in the coming months to hear as many views as possible across the country.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-23T17:04:37.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691869/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691869/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the implications for the farming sector of the UK leaving the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691870","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>Our National Atmospheric Emissions Inventory estimates that domestic combustion contributes 38% to our PM emissions. Our assessment finds the majority of this is from wood burning, either on an open fire or closed stove.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-23T14:47:34.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691870/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691870/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Wood-burning Stoves: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect on the environment of wood-burning stoves.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691871","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>Defra is committed to offering job applicants who are ex-offenders equal and fair opportunities. This commitment is supported through membership and operation of the Business in the Community ‘Ban the Box’ scheme. Following the principles in this scheme, appropriate pre-appointment checks, including a basic criminal record check, are not made until later in the recruitment process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, Defra does not retain details centrally that would allow us to identify employees with unspent convictions so the information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-23T15:57:07.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691871/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691871/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691872","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>This is a devolved matter. In England, between 31/1/16 to 31/1/17 the Environment Agency served a total of 5 notices upon landfill operators in England, of which 2 notices were served in the North East</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-23T10:38:09.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691872/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691872/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691872/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Landfill: Enforcement Notices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many enforcement notices have been taken out against landfill operators in the (a) UK and (b) North East in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","64530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691873","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Central Equine Database has been successfully tested with users. We will be piloting the database with Passport Issuing Organisations in March and expect it to be fully operational by summer 2017.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T11:22:45.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691873/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691873/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691873/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Horses: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made on the implementation of the Central Equine Database.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","64423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691874","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-02","<p>Sentencing is a matter for the courts, which are independent from government. When deciding what sentence to impose the courts take into account the circumstances of the offence and any mitigating and aggravating factors, in line with the sentencing guidelines.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-02T15:39:25.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691874/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691874/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to tackle unduly lenient sentencing for animal cruelty offences.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","64497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691875","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>Union vessels using hook and line methods have a directed fishing provision after February and March if they have a verified track record of catches, but it should be noted that bass catches by UK vessels using that method have tended to peak during the summer months from July to September. The Government does not intend to extend the moratorium period that has been agreed at EU level. However, my Department will of course continue to consider any new scientific advice on the state of the bass stock and the need for appropriate conservation measures.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T11:44:37.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691875/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691875/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Fisheries: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to support an extension of the commercial hook and line fishing moratorium into April, May and June 2017 in areas where there is evidence of spawning among bass stocks.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","64484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691876","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>Guidance was initially published by the Marine Management Organisation on 31 January 2017 to assist industry in understanding their obligations and the various requirements in respect of fishing for bass, as set out in Article 9 of Council Regulation (EU) 2017/127. Letters are being sent to all commerical fishermen within England and Wales who, based on their catch track records, have authorisation to catch bass, and to those who do not have such authorisation.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure compliance, the Marine Management Organisation will continue to engage with industry via regionally based staff to raise awareness of the rules, ensuring they are understood and individuals can access the right information easily. Where these rules are broken a proportionate and appropriate approach to enforcement action will be taken.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T11:47:20.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691876/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691876/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Fisheries: Quotas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to make commercial fishermen aware of new rules and enforcement measures to deter illegal netting of bass agreed by the Council and set out in Article 9 of Council Resolution (EU) 2017/127.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","64485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691877","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>The information requested is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>There were no pro bono costs.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Contracts</p></td><td><p>Contract Value (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>761</p></td><td><p>160,249,080</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>690</p></td><td><p>160,919,299</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>926</p></td><td><p>175,991,301</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>679</p></td><td><p>227,028,543</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>645</p></td><td><p>207,764,115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>419</p></td><td><p>127,572,806</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-28T15:20:58.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691877/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691877/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by her Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate she has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691878","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The UK is meeting limit values for all pollutants covered by the Ambient Air Quality Directive other than those for nitrogen dioxide (NO<sub>2</sub>). We will continue to do more, especially to reduce levels of NO<sub>2</sub>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will set out further measures this year, including consulting on a revised air quality plan on NO<sub>2</sub> by 24 April 2017 and publishing a final plan by 31 July 2017. The plan will set out the measures that will ensure the UK is compliant in the shortest time possible.</p><p> </p><p>In parallel, we are working to implement Clean Air Zones as quickly as possible. We are working closely with local authorities on the detailed design of the zones.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-27T11:13:01.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691878/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691878/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Air Pollution: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans for the UK to be compliant with the 2008 Ambient Air Quality Directive.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","64339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691879","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>My Department has not carried out estimates of the cost to the public purse of introducing mandatory food waste collections by local authorities in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-23T10:27:42.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691879/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691879/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate her Department has made of the potential cost to the public purse of introducing mandatory food waste collections by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","64349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691880","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>We do not intend to commission research into this. Manufacturing and retail supply chain food and packaging waste has reduced by 7.4% between 2009 and 2012, and a further 3% by 2015 by signatories under the previous Courtauld agreements. Under Courtauld 2025, we have a target to reduce total UK food waste by a further 20% by 2025.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-27T11:15:40.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691880/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691880/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Supermarkets: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will commission research into the operation of zero-waste grocery shops in overseas territories to identify potential benefits that such shops could bring to the UK.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691881","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>Core Defra did not make any payments to Uber for Business between 28 October 2016 and 21 February 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Staff within Core Defra who claim expenses for taxis used for work-related travel are not required to specify the name of the taxi company they used. The Department’s finance system lists only two transactions between 28 October 2016 and 21 February 2017 where the traveller has identified that they used Uber. These transactions total £13.99.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T11:19:34.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691881/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691881/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much her Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691882","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-28","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts for offences under the Hunting Act 2004, in England and Wales, in 2015, can be viewed in the table attached. Data for 2016 is planned for publication in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-28T11:03:54.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691882/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691882/answer","Hunting Act 2004, England and Wales, 2015.pdf","64671 table referred to","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691882/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Hunting Act 2004: Convictions and Criminal Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people were (a) proceeded against and (b) convicted of an offence under the Hunting Act 2004 in each police force area in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","64671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691883","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The UK is a Party to 35 Multilateral Environmental Agreements (MEAs) in its own right. These are mixed agreements and we are bound by the obligations they contain; this will not change on exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to continuing to play an active role internationally and will continue to be bound by the obligations under these MEAs after leaving the EU.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-02-27T15:01:19.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691883/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691883/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Environment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of which exclusive and mixed international environmental agreements in which the EU currently participates the Government plans to seek to be party to or otherwise maintain the provisions of after the UK leaves the EU; and which of those agreements (a) the Government will have to renegotiate and (b) will remain in force as the UK is a signatory in its own right.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","64664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691884","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>The following information was provided by the Ministry of Justice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts and found guilty at all courts for offences under the Protection of Badgers Act 1992, the Deer Act 1991 and the Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996, in England and Wales, in 2015, can be viewed in the attached table. Publication of 2016 data is planned for May 2017.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","64591 ; 64592","2017-02-23T15:01:45.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691884/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691884/answer","PQ 64591 64592 64648 - table.pdf","Defendants proceeded against at Magistrates Court","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691884/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Wild Mammals (Protection) Act 1996","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people were (a) proceeded against and (b) convicted of an offence under the Wild Animals (Protection) Act 1996 in each police force area in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","64648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691885","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Government would prefer animals to be slaughtered close to the point of production, however, the unilateral banning of live animal exports would be illegal under EU free trade rules. Once the UK has left the EU, there will be the possibility to consider further measures in this area.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-27T12:15:00.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691885/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691885/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691885/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-20","Livestock: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to introduce a ban on the export of live animals for slaughter.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","64580"
