"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691970","Home Office","false","2017-02-28","<p>The Home Office publishes accounting records, detailing where relevant, contracted-out services, within the Annual Reporting &amp; Accounts document at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ho-annual-reports-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/ho-annual-reports-and-accounts</a></p><p>The Home Office is committed to publishing all applicable contracts, over the value of £10,000 on the Contracts Finder website, at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a></p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-28T15:39:45.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691970/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691970/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Home Office: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by her Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate she has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691971","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The information requested is not recorded on Home Office systems. We do report on the number of decisions made an asylum claims, and, separately, on the number of persons detained for immigration purposes.</p><p>However, we do not have a combined set of data which would allow the question to be answered, and to cross-match these data sets over the period requested (since January 2014) would require a manual data matching exercise.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","64461 ; 64636 ; 64668","2017-02-23T12:19:22.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691971/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691971/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Asylum: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applicants were detained in each year between 2013 and 2017 whilst appealing a rejection of their application; and how many of those applicants were successful in appealing that decision.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","64416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691972","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The information requested is not recorded on Home Office systems. We do report on the number of decisions made an asylum claims, and, separately, on the number of persons detained for immigration purposes.</p><p>However, we do not have a combined set of data which would allow the question to be answered, and to cross-match these data sets over the period requested (since January 2014) would require a manual data matching exercise.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","64416 ; 64636 ; 64668","2017-02-23T12:19:21.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691972/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691972/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Asylum: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time spent in detention by an asylum applicant was in each year from 2013 to 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","64461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691973","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Home Office publishes, once a quarter, the average cost per day of immigration detention as part of Immigration Statistics. This can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>The Home Office is not able to calculate the average daily cost of short term holding facilities and immigration removal centres without incurring disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-27T10:33:08.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691973/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691973/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the daily cost to the public purse is of detaining an individual in (a) a short-term holding facility and (b) an immigration removal centre.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","64464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691974","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>Current legislation does not specify how this information needs to be recorded and it is not a statutory requirement in England to prepare or publish information in a particular format.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office uses Equality Impact Assessments (EIA) and Policy Equality Statements (PES) to detail equality considerations and demonstrate due regard has been paid in the delivery of our services, in line with our obligations under the Public Sector Equality duty.</p><p> </p><p>Home Office directorates are instructed to complete an EIA or a PES whenever;</p><p> </p><ul><li>There are changes to existing policy, guidance or operational activity</li><li>There are reviews of existing policy, guidance or operational activity</li><li>There are changes to policies that affect staff during restructuring</li></ul>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T11:38:46.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691974/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691974/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Home Office: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many equality impact assessments have been carried out in the last three years on public service reforms which impact on (a) departmental staff and (b) members of the public; and if she will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","64447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691975","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>In accordance with our international obligations, the UK is required to consider asylum and human rights applications carefully on their individual merits. The Government takes its international responsibilities seriously and will grant protection to those in genuine need.</p><p> </p><p>Each individual assessment of an asylum claim is made against the background of the latest available country of origin information and any relevant caselaw. The country of origin information is based on evidence taken from a range of reliable sources, including reputable media outlets; local, national and international organisations, including human rights organisations; and information from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office’s country of origin information, used in the asylum and other immigration decision making processes, is published on the gov.uk website. It is kept under constant review and updated periodically. Caseworkers also have access to an information request service for specific enquiries to deal with particular issues raised in individual applications.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-27T14:28:14.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691975/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691975/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Deportation: Cameroon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment the Government has made of the risks associated with returning English speaking failed asylum-seeking Cameroonians to Cameroon.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","64343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691976","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Home Office operates a ban the box policy in line with Cabinet Office guidance and does not ask for information about convictions at the start of the application process. We do not hold central records on how many employees have unspent convictions.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T11:37:29.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691976/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691976/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691976/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Home Office: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691977","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Home Office is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-27T11:33:21.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691977/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691977/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-20","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691978","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>DFID and other Departments, are working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawal will affect domestic policies.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-27T16:47:52.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691978/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691978/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the contents of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","64547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691979","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>DFID supports fair chance recruitment practices and uses the Civil Service wide recruitment system to advertise all jobs. This fully complies with the ‘Ban the Box’ policy.</p><p>The Cabinet Office mandated Baseline Personnel Security Standard (BPSS) requires all new recruits to declare unspent criminal convictions. Employees have a continued obligation to inform us of any criminal convictions received during employment with DFID.</p><p>To comply with our obligations under the Data Protection Act 1998, we do not routinely store this information and are unable to confirm how many employees have unspent convictions.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:45:02.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691979/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691979/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Department for International Development: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department operates a ban the box employment policy in respect of ex-offender job applicants with unspent convictions; and how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","64476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691980","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>Spend via contracts is approximately 13% of DFID’s annual spend with all partners. The total number and value of centrally awarded Government contracts contracted out by DFID in each year since 2010 is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of contracts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total value awarded</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>£277,462,339</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>£435,308,168</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>107</p></td><td><p>£772,914,731</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>£814,115,219</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>160</p></td><td><p>£1,002,033,206</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>£1,018,095,774</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The information on pro bono costs and work days is not held in the form requested and can only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:52:04.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691980/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691980/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Department for International Development: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the total (a) number and (b) value of Government contracts that have been contracted out by her Department was in each year since 2010; what the value of pro bono costs was in each such year; and what estimate she has made of the number of work days contracted out in each such year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691981","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>DFID does not have any contracts with Uber.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:41:44.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691981/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691981/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Department for International Development: Uber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on (a) Uber for Business and (b) other Uber transactions since 28 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","64378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691982","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>The UK is currently undertaking its assessment of the Palestinian Authority’s commitment to the Partnership Principles. These assessments provide robust analysis of countries’ commitments to these principles and are used to inform dialogue between DFID and partner governments.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:49:52.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691982/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691982/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when her Department will make its next assessment of the Palestinian Authority's compliance with the Partnership Principles set out in the Memorandum of Understanding between the UK and the Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","64352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691983","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>The PEGASE scheme is audited by two firms. Ernst &amp; Young are providing the ex-ante audits. The firm is authorised and regulated by the UK Solicitors Regulation Authority (SRA). Mazars, Paris (with their local partner El Wafa) are conducting ex-post audits. Mazars are regulated by Ordre des Experts Comptables – Région Paris Ile de France.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:50:28.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691983/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691983/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Palestinians: EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which body audits the PEGASE scheme; and which regulatory authority supervises those auditors.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","64353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691984","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>The PEGASE system uses a dedicated sub-account within the PA’s Single Treasury Account. The UK has a further sub-account to pay the salaries of West Bank health and education public servants. The PA payroll is checked by independent auditors, and UK payments made to all eligible beneficiaries are traced through the verification process.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:51:04.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691984/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691984/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Palestinians: EU Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether PEGASE uses a dedicated bank account to pay salaries to West Bank civil servants.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","64354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691985","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Global School Partnerships Programme (2003-12) was externally assessed by the National Foundation for Educational Research in 2011 and found to have a positive impact on the awareness, attitude and response of pupils in the UK towards global issues.</p><p>The 2012-15 phase of Connecting Classrooms was judged by an independent evaluation to be a success. Over 5,000 schools in more than 40 countries took part in joint projects and exchange visits and 18,000 teachers around the world benefitted from professional development training.</p><p>The current phase of Connecting Classrooms is being assessed annually.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:44:22.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691985/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691985/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Developing Countries: Educational Exchanges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of (a) the Global School Partnership programme and (b) the Connecting Classrooms programme.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","64654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691986","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>DFID has not specifically assessed the value of providing support to the Middle East Desalination Research Centre. Desalination is not a focus area for DFID’s water, health and sanitation portfolio and given the scale of private sector investment in this area, we do not have a strong comparative advantage that would support our involvement.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:41:20.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691986/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691986/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Oman: Desalination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2017 to Question 63588, what assessment her Department has made of the potential merits of providing support to the Middle East Desalination Research Centre in Oman.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","64666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691987","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>Through our support to the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, we protect children from violence, abuse, and exploitation. DFID also has specific programming targeting displaced children. For example, UK Aid in Syria and the region has provided over 920,000 children with psychosocial support, such as mental health care or psychosocial counselling.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:49:25.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691987/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691987/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to protect child refugees from exploitation, human trafficking and sexual violence.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","64692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691988","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>The 2015 UK Aid Strategy set out how the Government will strive to eliminate extreme poverty by 2030. This means supporting the world’s poorest people to ensure that every person has access to basic needs, including prioritising the rights of girls and women.</p><p>The Bilateral Development Review, published on 1 December 2016, set out what DFID will achieve over the next four years to deliver the UK’s commitment to reaching the poorest and most excluded people.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:40:18.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691988/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691988/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent steps the Government has taken to ensure that its overseas development aid is targeted at the world's poorest people.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","64626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691989","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>UK aid to the Palestinian Authority now only goes to the salaries of Palestinian Authority health and education public servants in the West Bank all of whom are able to work. No payments are made to Gaza public servants. These changes provide better value for money, with British taxpayers’ money able to deliver more essential services and have a bigger impact on the ground for Palestinians.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:56:07.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691989/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691989/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her announcement of 16 December 2017 on future UK support to the Occupied Palestinian Territories, whether the Government plans no longer to provide funds to the Palestinian Authority to pay salaries of (a) any Gaza public servants or (b) such servants who are unable to work.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","64650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691990","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>Around four per cent of UK official development assistance (ODA) was spent to support economic growth in middle-income countries in 2015.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T17:36:39.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691990/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691990/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of the Government's overseas development aid budget is spent on schemes to support economic growth in middle-income countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","64625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691991","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-23","<p>The ODI report identified important progress that has been made in supporting the fiscal stability of the Palestinian Authority, and made clear that DFID support was instrumental in reducing the chances of economic collapse of the Palestinian economy and violent escalation. The ODI report did not find, conclude or suggest that “paying salaries to convicted terrorists while they are in prison, and holding public sector jobs open for them until they are released from prison, appear[s] to have promoted terrorism in the period from 1998 to 2011” – this is misrepresentation of the research, its analysis and findings. The report made practical suggestions about how DFID could further improve its impact, which were taken into account in the design of the new programme of support to the PA.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-23T17:55:33.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691991/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691991/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the findings of the Overseas Development Institute report entitled Evaluative review of the Statebuilding Grant and the Palestinian Government Facility - DFID Palestinian programme, published by her Department in November 2015, that increased employment by the Palestinian Authority combined with its policies of paying salaries to convicted terrorists while they are in prison, and holding public sector jobs open for them until they are released from prison, appear to have promoted terrorism in the period from 1998 to 2011.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","64614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691992","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Government is committed to supporting Fairtrade around the world. Over the last six years, the Department for International Development (DfID) has provided £18 million to Fairtrade International to support their work and strengthen the global Fairtrade system. This includes Fairtrade producer and worker organizations that are the drivers of inclusive economic, environmental and social development in their communities around the world. DfID continues to actively engage with Fairtrade on a variety of projects and campaigns, such as the forthcoming Fairtrade Fortnight from 27 February to 12 March. Minister Stewart will be speaking at the All Party Parliamentary Group event marking the launch of Fairtrade Fortnight where he will meet Fairtrade campaigners from the UK and a Fairtrade coffee producer from Tanzania.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-27T16:39:00.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691992/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691992/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-02-20","Fairtrade Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to raise public awareness of Fair Trade.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","64574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691993","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-28","<p>Legal aid is a fundamental part of our justice system. We must ensure it is available for the individuals who need it, sustainable for the lawyers who provide it, and affordable for the taxpayers who ultimately pay for it.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's reform programme will deliver a justice system that is more accessible to the public. It aims to support people in resolving their disputes using simpler, modern procedures.</p><p> </p><p>This programme will modernise the courts and tribunal system improving the experience of everyone who comes into contact with it, including victims and witnesses. We will also make sure that the provision of legal support is updated to reflect the new way in which the justice system will work. We will publish a Green Paper on Legal Support next year.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-28T17:31:34.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691993/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691993/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps her Department has taken to secure the provision of legal aid for people on low incomes.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","64609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691994","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Attorney General and Justice Secretary are looking at how section 41 of the Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999 is working in practice. This includes examining the original policy intent of the legislation, its implementation and how it is currently operating.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice does not collect data on the number of victims of rape who appeared at Crown Courts in England and Wales and were asked about their sexual history by lawyers for the defence.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-27T16:43:09.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691994/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691994/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Rape: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information her Department holds on the number of victims of rape who appeared at Crown Courts in England and Wales and were asked about their sexual history by lawyers for the defence.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","64635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691995","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>An independent judiciary is the cornerstone of the rule of law and is a subject on which my department engages with international partners regularly.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","64017","2017-04-18T15:18:15.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691995/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691995/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Judiciary: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 20 February 2017 to Question 63942, if she will raise the issue of the importance of an independent judiciary with Jeff Sessions, Attorney General of the US.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691996","Department of Health","false","2017-02-23","<p>Due to the integrated approach to prison healthcare services commissioning by NHS England, this information is not available.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-23T10:16:59.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691996/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691996/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-20","Prisons: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been spent from the public purse on drug rehabilitation services in prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691997","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>Information and guidance to maximise the use of volunteers, including ex-offenders and serving prisoners, has been commissioned by the Ministry of Justice and was published in July 2016 by Clinks, the umbrella group for voluntary organisations working with offenders and their families. The Department is committed to continuing and increasing the use of volunteers, and encouraging appropriate volunteering opportunities for ex-offenders within rehabilitation services and elsewhere.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-27T11:53:42.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691997/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691997/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Offenders: Voluntary Work","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government plans to introduce a volunteering programme for ex-offenders.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","64653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691998","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Victims’ Code is freely available online, but we know more must be done to support and protect victims. We have made positive steps to improve the experience of victims, by reducing unnecessary stress and emotional turmoil of attending court. We have also reconvened the Victims’ Panel, so we can learn from the experiences of victims of crime.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Victims’ Code those victims who feel that their rights have not been met can complain directly to the criminal justice agency concerned, and if they remain dissatisfied can take their complaint to the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman. We are currently considering how compliance with the Victims’ Code might be improved and monitored, and exploring how those delivering services can be better held to account. Plans to engage with and obtain the views of victims and victims’ groups and criminal justice agencies are being developed. We will set out our strategy for victims within 12 months, and will bring forward any appropriate primary legislation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","64533","2017-03-06T15:59:15.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691998/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691998/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how agencies in the criminal justice system are held accountable for any failures to comply with the Code of Practice for Victims of Crime.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","64646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691999","Department for Education","false","2017-02-28","<p>Keeping Children Safe in Education is the statutory guidance to which all schools and colleges in England must regard when carrying out their duties to safeguard and promote the welfare of children. The guidance places a responsibility on all staff to provide a safe environment, in which children can learn and to consider at all times what is in the best interests of the child.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance requires schools and colleges to have an effective child protection policy, which includes procedures to minimise the risk of peer on peer abuse and sets out how allegations of peer on peer abuse will be investigated. The policy should reflect the different forms that peer on peer abuse may take and make clear that abuse should never be tolerated or passed off as banter or part of growing up. The policy should also be clear as to how victims of peer on peer abuse will be supported. The guidance is clear that children’s social care and the Police should be involved as appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>Following the recent Women and Equalities report into sexual harassment and sexual violence in schools, the Department for Education has committed to reviewing existing departmental guidance, including Keeping Children Safe in Education. An advisory group has been set up to support the department in this work.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-28T17:08:08.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691999/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/691999/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-20","Sexual Offences: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance is available for schools on appropriate procedures for dealing with allegations of pupil-on-pupil sexual assault.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692000","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>We want to make sure the needs of victims and witnesses are at the heart of a modern justice system. That is why it is vital we learn as much as possible from the experience of real life victims and survivors of crime.</p><p>We have re-established the Victims’ Panel so we can get direct feedback from victims and we are keen to continue and develop their valuable contribution. The Victims’ Panel reconvened on the 6 February 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-27T16:37:25.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692000/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692000/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Victims' Panel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she plans to extend the membership of her Department's Victims' Panel.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692001","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-23","<p>To begin the process of reviewing the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 (LASPO), the Government plans to submit a Post Legislative Memorandum to the Justice Select Committee in a few months’ time. We will outline our plans for the post-implementation review (PIR) of LASPO in more detail when we submit the memorandum to Parliament. The PIR will cover the reforms to legal aid made by LASPO. We intend to work closely with key parties across the sector to inform the review’s conclusions.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","64633 ; 64689","2017-02-23T16:57:58.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692001/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692001/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will publish the scope of the review into the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","64634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692002","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>We have made positive steps to improve the experience of victims, to reduce unnecessary stress and lessen the emotional turmoil of attending court. But we have been clear that more must be done. That is why we will set out our strategy for victims within 12 months, including bringing forward any appropriate legislation.</p><p> </p><p>We are actively considering how compliance with the Code of Practice for Victims of Crime (Victims’ Code) might be improved and monitored. We are also exploring how those responsible for delivery of rights and entitlements might be better held accountable for any failings.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","64619","2017-02-27T16:39:59.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692002/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692002/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whom her Department plans to consult for the 12 month review of the working of the Code of Practice for the Victims of Crime.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","64620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692003","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>Sentencing guidelines are issued by the independent Sentencing Council for England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>As the government are actively considering offences and penalties in this area the Council have postponed their review of sentencing guidelines for causing death by driving.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-27T16:43:00.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692003/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692003/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Dangerous Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of reviewing the sentencing guidelines applicable to offences involving deaths caused by driving.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","64629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692004","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-03","<p>All Ministry of Justice employees are required to complete a mandatory Equality and Diversity training module which makes specific reference to mental health conditions and supporting vulnerable customers. In addition, Mental Health Awareness courses have also been delivered to employees across the country and frontline court training materials also link into the ‘Every Witness Matters’ handbook to ensure that employees are aware of the potential impact that a mental health condition may have on a court user. Colleagues working in National Business Centres have been provided with specific training on ‘Dealing with Traumatic Calls’.</p><p> </p><p>Under the Constitutional Reform Act 2005, responsibility for the training of the judiciary rests with the Lord Chief Justice as Head of the Judiciary. Training on mental health issues is limited to awareness in order to help judges ensure that all court users are treated equally and fairly. Judges are able to access advice and guidance on this through the Equal Treatment Bench Book which is publicly available at: <a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/publications/equal-treatment-bench-book/" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/publications/equal-treatment-bench-book/</a></p><p> </p><p>Data relating specifically to the effectiveness of the training is not held but the department is committed to the continued development of initiatives to ensure employees can support customers who may be suffering from a mental health condition.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","64632","2017-03-03T15:03:14.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692004/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692004/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-20","Administration of Justice: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessments she has made of the effectiveness of the training provided to (a) court staff and (b) members of the judiciary on identifying and supporting court users with a mental health condition.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","64631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/692005","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-28","<p>The number of restraining orders issued and sentences given for breaches of restraining orders, from 2013 to 2015, in England and Wales, can be viewed in the following tables.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2016 are planned for publication in May 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Table 1: Restraining orders issued by the courts and offenders convicted and sentenced for breach of restraining orders, with sentencing outcomes, England &amp; Wales, 2013 to 2015<sup>(1)(2)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2013<sup>(3)</sup></p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Restraining orders issued<sup>(4)(5)(6)</sup></p></td><td><p>20,356</p></td><td><p>21,508</p></td><td><p>23,057</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Offenders convicted of breaching a restraining order</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Convicted</p></td><td><p>6,348</p></td><td><p>7,371</p></td><td><p>8,395</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sentenced</p></td><td><p>6,205</p></td><td><p>7,083</p></td><td><p>8,194</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Immediate custody</p></td><td><p>2,237</p></td><td><p>2,606</p></td><td><p>2,989</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Suspended sentence</p></td><td><p>827</p></td><td><p>1,068</p></td><td><p>1,346</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Community sentence</p></td><td><p>1,565</p></td><td><p>1,524</p></td><td><p>1,815</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fine</p></td><td><p>848</p></td><td><p>1,020</p></td><td><p>1,137</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Absolute discharge</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>57</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Conditional discharge</p></td><td><p>469</p></td><td><p>532</p></td